			"contents": "# April 8\n\n## Models of DNA Evolution\n\nThe first reading covers the early development of molecular phylogenetic methods, and is a fun read. It is a great summary of parsimony and distance methods and philosophical differences. Think about this as you ponder the implicit assumptions about characters, homology, individuality, and what we are actually estimating with a phylogeny. \n\nHere are some \\[[notes](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1_1Pk_apn52n0IibvKzE78gsirtYb3yx58QSz9Zt9xYk/edit?tab=t.0)\\] developed by a previous class\n\nThe second reading is a detailed run through of models of DNA evolution, in a mathematically explicit (mechanistic) way. It requires some effort, but once it becomes clear it is beautifully simple, and is well worth the effort for the deeper understanding you will achieve. \n\n37. __Felsenstein, J. 2004. Chapter 10__ A digression on History and Philosophy. 123-147 in Inferring Phylogenies. Sinauer Assoc., Sunderland.  \n38. __Felsenstein, J. 2004. Chapter 13__ Models of DNA evolution. Pp. 196-221 in Inferring Phylogenies. Sinauer Assoc., Sunderland.  \n\n### FYI:\n\nEdwards, Cavalli-Sforza 1963. The reconstruction of evolution. Annals of Human Genetics 27: 105-106. (Also published in Heredity 18:553).  __Look how short!!!__\n\nEdwards, Cavalli-Sforza 1964. Reconstruction of evolutionary trees. pp. 67-76 in PHenetic and phylogenetic classification, V. H. Heywood and J. McNeill (eds.) Systematics Association Publ. No. 6, London.  \n\n\n",
